Individual deposit growth

Daniel P. Egan

12/20/2018

Setup

Whats the relationship between time weighted returns and earnings? Should an investor ever expect to have higher TWR than earnings percent?

Lets use VTSMX to find out.

Below we show a steady investor, who always deposits $10 every month into the S&P 500. Sometimes they deposit before a fall, sometimes before a rise. On average, things go up though.

Over time, those consistent deposits add up. The growth of the market doesnt hurt either. But there are some points where the portfolio is worth less than its net deposits.

Whats happening here? Well, lets look at the growth of each individual deposit. The graph below breaks out each individual deposit to show the specific return it generates.

They all start at $10, but then grow up and down with market movements. Older deposits are red, and younger deposits are yellow. There are a few cases of yellow (newer) deposits being above older (redder) deposits, but theyre few and far between. These yellow-above-red are deposits that occurred just before a market bounce. Thats luck, not skill thought. Were just doing monthly deposits.

This is the same plot, but with all deposits having the same starting point.

The experience
